      <div class="thesis-body">
        <p style="font-size: 17px; color: var(--ink); line-height: 1.55;">Marketo shipped v1 in 2006. The premise was Salesforce as the source of truth, email as the only channel, and the lead as the atom of marketing.</p>

        <div class="thesis-quote">
          Every one of those premises is now wrong for a specific segment of B2B.
        </div>

        <p>Warehouse-native SaaS companies have their customer reality in Snowflake and BigQuery, not in CRM fields. Modern B2B runs across Slack Connect, product events, and community channels. The <strong>account</strong> is the atom of marketing now, not the lead.</p>

        <p>Legacy MAPs like Marketo, HubSpot, and SFMC did not get worse. They got wrong for a new category of buyer. And the modern point tools, Hightouch and Iterable and Customer.io, each solve one slice and leave a duct-tape operation behind.</p>

        <p>Conversion is the first MAP built for how modern B2B actually works. Pylon did this to Zendesk by owning "B2B support on Slack Connect" before Zendesk realized it was a category. Conversion can do this to Marketo by owning "warehouse-native B2B marketing automation" before Adobe realizes the center of gravity moved.</p>

        <div class="thesis-quote">
          "Pick an emerging trend in a big market, then compete against large, slow-moving incumbents who aren't focused on a particular niche."
          <cite>Marty Kausas, Co-founder of Pylon, on how they took $2B of Zendesk ARR apart one logo at a time</cite>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Competitive Map (within thesis) -->
